Two hours. 15 tables ahead of us. My civic project team and I stood in the cold, waiting to get into a restaurant in Gangnam. To my "why don't we just go somewhere else," the answer from our local partner was, "It's okay to wait. Other places will have the same queue anyway."

I didn't know at that moment that I was experiencing a Korean cultural phenomenon called open run.

Open run means standing in a long line, waiting to enter a restaurant or shop. The phenomenon has long existed in South Korea, but the term open run [was coined during the COVID-19](https://www.koreaherald.com/article/3184730) pandemic, when the number of customers allowed in stores was limited. You probably think that queuing exists everywhere. But Seoul has taken it to another level.

The point of open run is not even getting the final reward — tasting that popular bagel or buying those shoes — it's simply about the experience of waiting itself. People line up without even knowing what they're waiting for.

One Reddit user shared their story about line waiting in Korea: they just joined the queue for fun only to find out that it was a beef intestines restaurant. The user was vegetarian.

[Some see](https://www.koreaherald.com/article/3184730) open runs as a badge of loyalty: a customer, interviewed by *The Korea Herald* while waiting in line for limited-edition sneakers, stated, "I felt that this was a chance to show my devotion to the team as a fan." Similarly, a feature by Sung Ji Yeon highlighted a bakery where customers described their hours-long wait as "the best wait ever."

In Seoul, waiting isn't seen as a waste of time. It's a social activity, a shared experience. There's the idea of *sohwakhaeng* (small but certain happiness), where even the wait becomes part of the pleasure, building anticipation that makes that first sip of coffee or bite of trending salt bread taste even better. But in a city where trends move fast and FOMO runs high, the open run phenomenon can also heighten the fear of missing out, turning the pursuit of happiness into a race.

Of course, tech entrepreneurs have already hopped on this trend and come up with app ideas. Queue-tracking apps now let you see real-time wait times before you even leave your house. Some places use digital ticketing systems so you can check in, go elsewhere, and return when it's your turn.

Beyond that, businesses have started adapting to the waiting culture. Instead of letting long lines deter customers, they turn them into an experience. Pop-up shops hand out freebies to those in line. Restaurants offer menus to browse while you wait. Some places have even created "zero-order spaces" — designated waiting zones near popular spots.

You have probably seen long queues here in Seoul, and most likely, you decided not to stay in them. But if we embrace cultural immersion, let's embrace it in all of its forms. Open run is a uniquely Korean experience, something you won't find in the same way anywhere else.

If you're curious to try an open run for yourself, there are plenty of places in Seoul known for gathering serious queues. Tosokchon Samgyetang near Gyeongbokgung Palace is famous for its ginseng chicken soup and always has a line. Ikseon-dong's hidden cafés like Cheongsudang get packed even before opening. Geumdwaeji Sikdang in Mapo serves grilled pork belly, and people start lining up as early as 10 a.m. For pastries, the recent salt bread trend has created long lines outside places like Maybell Bakery and Tartine in Hannam.

So next time you see a long line, join it. You might just have the best wait of your life.

